Air Quality (AQI)

Particulate Matter 2.5 (\(\text{PM}_{2.5}\)) describes fine inhalable particles in the atmosphere with diameters that are generally 2.5 micrometers and smaller. Air quality, as measured by \(\text{PM}_{2.5}\), is an often cited proxy for poor health1. In Canvas, there is a dataset “hr_aqi.csv” which contains (nearly) daily air quality measurements from the Hampton Roads Core Based Statistical Area from 2006 to present.

Aggregate these data to the quarterly level, and predict AQI levels (“DAILY_AQI_VALUE”) in 2020 until present using the following models:

  1. Fit an intercept only model.
  2. Fit a trend model.
  3. Fit a (few) trend model(s) with a kink.
    1. Pick your own kink date.
    2. Let the data pick the best date.
    3. Fit a trend model using data only AFTER the trend kink date, much like the third model from the question above.
  4. Which model did the best at forecasting? Use root mean square error2 (RMSE) as your criteria.
library("lubridate")
library("scales")
library("stargazer")
library("gridExtra")
library("janitor")
library("tidyverse")
library("ggplot2")

aqi <- readRDS("../data/hr_aqi.RDS")
# change the date to quarterly
aqi <- aqi %>% 
  mutate(Date = floor_date(ymd(Date), "quarter"))


# aggregate data
hr <- aqi %>% 
  group_by(q = Date) %>% 
  summarize(aqi = mean(DAILY_AQI_VALUE), .groups = "drop") %>%
  mutate(t = interval(min(q), q) %/% months(3),
         t_break = if_else(q >= ymd("2015-01-01"), 1, 0),
         t2 = interval(ymd("2015-01-01"), q) %/% months(3))

# define horizon (testing sample)
horizon <- hr$q >= ymd("2020-01-01")

# Regression models
reg_int <- lm(aqi ~ 1, data = hr[!horizon, ])
reg_trend <- lm(aqi ~ t, data = hr[!horizon, ])
reg_kink1 <- lm(aqi ~ t + t2:t_break, data = hr[!horizon,])

# Calculate R-squared for multiple models
rsqr <- map_dbl(8:52, function(i) {
  hr <- hr %>%
    mutate(t_break2 = if_else(t > i, 1, 0),
           t22 = t - i)
  
  reg_tmp <- lm(aqi ~ t + t22:t_break2, data = hr[!horizon, ])
  summary(reg_tmp)$r.squared
})


# update hr with new break values using the highest r square
break_val <- (8:52)[which.max(rsqr)]
hr <- hr %>% 
  mutate(t_break2 = if_else(t > break_val, 1, 0),
         t2 = t - break_val)


# Final regression model
reg_kink2 <- lm(aqi ~ t + t2:t_break2, data = hr[!horizon, ])
reg_kink3 <- lm(aqi ~ t, data = hr[!horizon & hr$t_break2 == 1, ])
library("stargazer")
stargazer(reg_int, reg_trend, reg_kink1, reg_kink2, reg_kink3,
          type = "html", omit.stat = c("f", "ser"))

ggplot(hr, aes(x = q, y = aqi)) + 
  geom_line(aes(), color = alpha("black", .4), size = 1) +  # The main line for AQI
  geom_line(data = subset(hr, horizon), aes(), color = alpha("black", 1),size = 1) +  # Actual line
  
  # Lines for different regression fitted values
  geom_line(data = subset(hr, !horizon), aes(y = reg_int$fitted.values), linetype = 2, color = alpha("red", .5)) +

# calculate RMSE for the predictions

rmse <- function(model){
  
  a <- hr$aqi[horizon]
  f <- predict(model, newdata = hr[horizon,])
  
  sqrt(mean((a-f)^2))
}

print("RMSE:")
c("Intercept" = rmse(reg_int),
  "Trend" = rmse(reg_trend),
  "Kink1" = rmse(reg_kink1),
  "Kink2" = rmse(reg_kink2),
  "Kink3" = rmse(reg_kink3))

Population

Choose one country that starts with the same letter as your first name, and another for your last name 3. Consider data from 1960 to 2010 as your sample period.

  1. Use trends to forecast population in levels. Be sure to include and explain any modeling decisions. Evaluate your forecasts using both RMSE and MAPE4.
  2. Use trends to forecast population in growth rates (i.e. percent change). Be sure to include and explain any modeling decisions. Evaluate your forecasts using both RMSE and MAPE.
pop <- read.csv("../data/country_pop.csv") %>% clean_names()
angola <- pop %>% filter(country_name == "Angola")
china <- pop %>% filter(country_name == "China")

pop <- data.frame(year = 1960:2021,
                  angola = t(angola[,5:ncol(china)]),
                  china = t(china[,5:ncol(china)]))
colnames(pop) <- c("year", "angola", "china")

pop <- pop %>%
  arrange(year) %>%
  mutate(
    angola_pc = (angola - lag(angola)) / lag(angola),
    china_pc = (china - lag(china)) / lag(china)
  )

horizon <- pop$year > 2010

rmse <- function(model, outcome_var) {
  
  a <- filter(pop, horizon)[[outcome_var]]
  f <- predict(model, newdata = filter(pop, horizon))
  
  sqrt(mean((a-f)^2))
}

mape <- function(model, outcome_var){
  
  a <- filter(pop, horizon)[[outcome_var]]
  f <- predict(model, newdata = filter(pop, horizon))
  
  mean(abs((a - f) / a))
}


# Linear models
reg_a <- lm(asinh(angola) ~ year, data = filter(pop, !horizon & year > 1970))
reg_c <- lm(china ~ asinh(year), data = filter(pop, !horizon))


# Predictions for the horizon
a <- filter(pop, horizon)$angola
f <- sinh(predict(reg_a, newdata = filter(pop, horizon)))

rmse_vec <- c(sqrt(mean((f - a)^2)), rmse(reg_c, "china"))
mape_vec <- c(mean(abs((a - f) / a)), mape(reg_c, "china"))

pop$angola_pred <- sinh(predict(reg_a, pop))
pop$china_pred <- predict(reg_c, pop)



# Plot for Angola
p1 <- ggplot(pop, aes(x = year)) + 
  geom_line(aes(y = angola/1000000), color = "black") +
  geom_line(aes(y = angola_pred/1000000), color = "tomato") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 2009.5, linetype = 2) +
  labs(
    title = "Angola",
    y = "Population (Levels, Millions)",
    x = ""
  ) + 
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_color_identity(name = "", breaks = c("black", "tomato"), labels = c("Actual", "Fitted"))

# Plot for China
p2 <- ggplot(pop, aes(x = year)) + 
  geom_line(aes(y = china/1000000), color = "black") +
  geom_line(aes(y = china_pred/1000000), color = "tomato") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 2009.5, linetype = 2) +
  labs(
    title = "China",
    y = "Population (Levels, Millions)",
    x = ""
  ) + 
  theme_minimal()

# Display plots side by side

grid.arrange(p1, p2, ncol = 2)

# Linear models
reg_a <- lm(angola_pc ~ year, data = filter(pop, !horizon & year > 1979))
reg_c <- lm(china_pc ~ year, data = filter(pop, !horizon & year > 1969))

rmse_vec <- c(rmse_vec, rmse(reg_a, "angola_pc"), rmse(reg_c, "china_pc"))
mape_vec <- c(mape_vec, mape(reg_a, "angola_pc"), mape(reg_c, "china_pc"))

pop <- pop %>%
  mutate(
    angola_pred = predict(reg_a, .),
    china_pred = predict(reg_c, .)
  )

# Plot for Angola
p1 <- ggplot(pop, aes(x = year)) + 
  geom_line(aes(y = angola_pc), color = "black") +
  geom_line(aes(y = angola_pred), color = "tomato") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 2009.5, linetype = 2) +
  labs(
    title = "Angola",
    y = "Population (Growth)",
    x = ""
  ) + 
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_color_identity(name = "", breaks = c("black", "tomato"), labels = c("Actual", "Fitted"))

# Plot for China
p2 <- ggplot(pop, aes(x = year)) + 
  geom_line(aes(y = china_pc), color = "black") +
  geom_line(aes(y = china_pred), color = "tomato") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 2009.5, linetype = 2) +
  labs(
    title = "China",
    y = "Population (Growth)",
    x = ""
  ) + 
  theme_minimal()


grid.arrange(p1, p2, ncol = 2)
